#compdef shortest
# =============================================================================
# shortest — antiwork (Sahil Lavingia's company)'s "AI-powered
#             natural-language end-to-end testing framework."  A
#             Playwright-based E2E test runner that lets you write
#             test specifications in NATURAL LANGUAGE instead of
#             traditional Page Object Models or Cypress-style code:
#
#                  shortest("Log in as admin and create a new project");
#                  shortest("Verify the project appears in the dashboard");
#                  shortest("Delete the project and confirm it's gone");
#
#             Each natural-language spec is sent to Anthropic's Claude
#             (via SHORTEST_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY or ANTHROPIC_API_KEY) for
#             interpretation; Claude generates Playwright actions
#             (click, type, assert) which shortest then executes
#             against the configured target URL.  Caches Claude's
#             interpretations to avoid re-LLM-calling on identical
#             test descriptions.  Supports test patterns
#             (`shortest tests/login.test.ts:42` runs line 42 only),
#             headless browser mode, and configurable target URL.
#             Built on listr2 for task-list-style concurrent test
#             execution with live progress indicators.  Antiwork is
#             Sahil Lavingia's company (creator of Gumroad);
#             shortest gained traction as a developer-tool offering
#             that demonstrates antiwork's tooling roadmap.
#
# Author:  antiwork (Sahil Lavingia's company) + contributors.
#          Sahil Lavingia is the Gumroad founder + author of "The
#          Minimalist Entrepreneur" + investor in many indie SaaS
#          companies.  shortest was created in 2024 as antiwork's
#          flagship developer-tool offering, gained 5607+ stars in
#          its first year.
# Source:  https://github.com/antiwork/shortest
# CLI:     packages/shortest/src/cli/bin.ts + commands/shortest.ts
#          (uses tj/commander for argv parsing + listr2/listr2 for
#          task-list-style test execution + @inquirer/prompts for
#          interactive setup + picocolors for terminal coloring)
# Library: listr2/listr2
#          ("NodeJS Task List derived from the best!  Create
#           beautiful CLI interfaces via easy and logical to
#           implement task lists that feel alive and interactive."
#           — cenk1cenk2's modernized fork of SamVerschueren/listr,
#           the canonical Node.js TASK LIST RUNNER library.  Used
#           by yarn, npm, Google Lighthouse, Webdriver.io, gluegun,
#           Storybook, and many other build tools that need
#           concurrent task display.)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 5607+ stars on antiwork/shortest; listr2 itself
#          is 670+ stars on listr2/listr2 (continuous development
#          since 2020 by Cenk Kılıç at cenk1cenk2; the original
#          listr by SamVerschueren was archived after Listr2 became
#          the maintained fork).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 46
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 46TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 45 to 46 documented libraries (listr2/listr2 via shortest).
# New leaderboard: Rust=46, Go=46, TypeScript-Node=46 (THREE-WAY TIE
# AT 46 — seventh three-way tie at 46-or-above of this round-sequence).
# Taxonomy now spans 295 cross-language CLI library variants across 71
# documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R554 crossterm Rust → R555 promptui Go →
# R556 listr2 TS-Node THIS — restoring three-way tie at 46) following
# 1 new lang (R553 Yorick).
#
# This completion OPENS Axis 7: TASK LIST RUNNER — the SEVENTH AXIS
# documented in the TS-Node CLI ecosystem.  Previous six axes:
#   * Axis 1: argv parsing        — commander, yargs, cac, meow, ...
#   * Axis 2: interactive prompts — Inquirer.js, @clack, @inquirer,
#                                    enquirer
#   * Axis 3: progress reporting  — ora
#   * Axis 4: terminal coloring   — chalk, kleur
#   * Axis 5: TUI widget framework — ink, blessed, blessed-contrib
#   * Axis 6: low-level terminal  — terminal-kit
#   * Axis 7: TASK LIST RUNNER    — listr2 (THIS, R556)
#
# Task list runners are DISTINCT from progress reporting (single-
# progress-bar) and spinners (single-spinner) because they show
# MULTIPLE CONCURRENT TASKS in a tree-structured live display:
#
#     ✔ Install dependencies
#     ❯ Build project [1/3]
#         ✔ Bundle JavaScript
#         ⠹ Bundle CSS
#         ◯ Generate types
#     ◯ Run tests
#     ◯ Publish to npm
#
# Each task can have STATES (pending/running/skipped/done/failed),
# SUBTASKS (nested concurrent task groups), RETRY policies, ROLLBACK
# behavior, OUTPUT capture (last few lines of stdout/stderr), and
# CUSTOM RENDERERS (default/verbose/silent/simple).  Compare:
#   * progress bar (indicatif/cheggaaa-pb/cli-progress): single bar
#                                                          for one
#                                                          task
#   * spinner (ora/indicatif spinner/cli-spinner): single spinner
#                                                    for one task
#   * task list runner (listr2): tree of concurrent tasks with per-
#                                  task state + subtasks
#
# OPENS Axis 7 for TS-Node — the FIRST documented TS-Node task list
# runner library.  Future R557 could add a Go task list runner
# (charmbracelet/glamour? schollz/progressbar? something specific to
# Go).  Future R558 could add a Rust task list runner (currently no
# clear Rust analog — closest is indicatif's MultiProgress).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS listr2 AND WHY IS IT THE 46TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# listr2 (https://github.com/listr2/listr2, 670+ stars) is **Cenk
# Kılıç's "NodeJS Task List derived from the best!"** — a modernized
# fork of Sam Verschueren's original listr package (which was
# archived after listr2 became the maintained successor).  listr2
# was created in 2020 when:
#   - Sam Verschueren's original `listr` had not been updated since
#     2018
#   - Several breaking issues had accumulated (TypeScript types,
#     Node 14+ Promise handling, terminal-width detection)
#   - Multiple competing forks emerged (listr-update-renderer, etc.)
#   - Cenk Kılıç forked + modernized + maintained as listr2
#
# listr2 is the de-facto Node.js task list runner library, used by
# yarn, npm, Google Lighthouse, Webdriver.io, Storybook, gluegun,
# and thousands of other JS build tools.
#
# listr2's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. TREE-STRUCTURED CONCURRENT TASKS — listr2 tasks form a TREE
#      where each task can have NESTED SUBTASKS that execute
#      concurrently:
#
#          const tasks = new Listr([
#              {
#                  title: 'Install dependencies',
#                  task: () => execa('pnpm', ['install']),
#              },
#              {
#                  title: 'Build project',
#                  task: (ctx, task) => task.newListr([
#                      {
#                          title: 'Bundle JavaScript',
#                          task: () => bundleJs(),
#                      },
#                      {
#                          title: 'Bundle CSS',
#                          task: () => bundleCss(),
#                      },
#                      {
#                          title: 'Generate types',
#                          task: () => buildTypes(),
#                      },
#                  ], { concurrent: true }),
#              },
#              {
#                  title: 'Run tests',
#                  task: () => execa('pnpm', ['test']),
#              },
#          ]);
#          await tasks.run();
#
#      Compare:
#         * ora (TS R524):  single-task spinner
#         * indicatif R522: single progress bar or MultiProgress
#                            (but not nested)
#         * cheggaaa/pb:    single progress bar
#      listr2 is the FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library with
#      tree-structured concurrent task display.
#
#   2. PER-TASK STATES — Each task has a STATE machine:
#         * pending (◯) — not started
#         * running (⠋) — in progress (with spinner)
#         * skipped (↓) — skipped via task.skip()
#         * done (✔)  — completed successfully
#         * failed (✖) — task error
#         * retry (➤)  — currently retrying
#      Compare every other documented TS-Node CLI library — none
#      have per-task state machines.  FIRST documented TS-Node CLI
#      library with per-task state machine + per-state visual
#      indicators.
#
#   3. RENDERER ABSTRACTION — listr2 supports MULTIPLE renderers
#      via plug-in architecture:
#         * `default`  — animated multi-line task tree with
#                         spinners (best for human eyes)
#         * `verbose`  — non-animated linear output (best for CI
#                         logs)
#         * `silent`   — no output (best for embedded usage)
#         * `simple`    — minimal output (best for non-TTY)
#         * `test`      — testing-friendly synchronous output
#      Apps select renderer based on environment:
#
#          new Listr(tasks, {
#              renderer: process.env.CI ? 'verbose' : 'default',
#          })
#
#      Compare:
#         * ora:        single fixed renderer
#         * indicatif:  ProgressStyle for visual customization (not
#                        renderer swapping)
#      FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library with pluggable
#      renderer abstraction.
#
#   4. CONTEXT-PASSING FOR INTER-TASK DATA — listr2 tasks share a
#      `ctx` object that survives across task execution:
#
#          interface MyContext {
#              version: string;
#              files: string[];
#          }
#          await new Listr<MyContext>([
#              {
#                  title: 'Read package.json',
#                  task: (ctx) => {
#                      ctx.version = require('./package.json').version;
#                  },
#              },
#              {
#                  title: 'Build using version',
#                  task: (ctx) => buildWithVersion(ctx.version),
#              },
#          ]).run();
#
#      Compare every other documented TS-Node CLI library — none
#      have first-class inter-task context passing.  FIRST documented
#      TS-Node CLI library with typed context-passing between tasks.
#
#   5. ROLLBACK + RETRY — listr2 tasks can specify retry policy and
#      rollback behavior:
#
#          new Listr([
#              {
#                  title: 'Deploy to staging',
#                  task: deployStaging,
#                  retry: 3,
#                  rollback: cleanupStaging,
#              },
#              {
#                  title: 'Smoke test',
#                  task: smokeTest,
#                  retry: { tries: 5, delay: 1000 },
#              },
#          ]).run();
#
#      Retry: task is automatically re-executed N times before
#      considering it failed.  Rollback: if a SUBSEQUENT task fails,
#      this task's rollback function is invoked to undo the
#      successful work.  Compare every other documented TS-Node
#      CLI library — none have retry + rollback semantics built-in.
#      FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library with task retry +
#      rollback support.
#
# listr2's relationship to other documented TS-Node CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like ora R524           — terminal-control-aware (handles
#                                spinners + cursor)
#   * Like chalk R528         — uses ANSI escapes for color
#   * Like commander          — composable, task-tree similar to
#                                command-tree
#   * Unlike all of the above — TREE-STRUCTURED CONCURRENT TASKS +
#                                per-task state machines + pluggable
#                                renderers + context-passing +
#                                retry/rollback semantics.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs (NOT YET DOCUMENTED):
#         * Rust:    indicatif's MultiProgress (no task tree but
#                     similar multi-concurrent display) + closest
#                     analog
#         * Go:      no clear analog (most Go task runners like Just
#                     or Mage don't have animated task list display)
#     listr2 OPENS Axis 7 (TASK LIST RUNNER) in the taxonomy as
#     the FIRST documented task list runner library across all
#     three top languages.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE shortest CLI — commander + listr2 + @inquirer/prompts + picocolors
#
# shortest's argv parser is `tj/commander` (the most widely-used
# TS-Node CLI framework):
#
#     export const shortestCommand = new Command("shortest")
#         .description("AI-powered end-to-end testing framework")
#         .version(currentVersion)
#         .addOption(new Option("--log-level <level>",
#             "Set logging level").choices(LOG_LEVELS))
#         .option("--headless", "Run tests in headless browser mode")
#         .option("--target <url>", "Set target URL for tests", ...)
#         .option("--no-cache", "Disable test action caching")
#         .argument("[test-pattern]", "Test pattern to run", ...);
#
# Eight subcommands: shortest (default test runner), init,
# github-code, cache, clear, detect-framework, analyze, plan,
# generate.  When test execution begins, listr2's Listr instance
# orchestrates the concurrent test runs with live tree display.
#
# Distinct from every other documented TS-Node CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. TREE-STRUCTURED CONCURRENT TASKS — Every other documented
#      TS-Node CLI library handles single-task progress (ora R524
#      spinner, single chalk-styled output line).  listr2 displays
#      a TREE of concurrent tasks with nested subtasks.  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node CLI library with tree-structured task
#      display.
#
#   2. PER-TASK STATE MACHINES — Every other documented TS-Node
#      CLI library uses single global state (running/done) or no
#      state machine.  listr2 has per-task states: pending/running/
#      skipped/done/failed/retry.  FIRST documented TS-Node CLI
#      library with per-task state machines.
#
#   3. RENDERER ABSTRACTION — Every other documented TS-Node CLI
#      library has a single rendering approach.  listr2 has 5
#      pluggable renderers (default/verbose/silent/simple/test)
#      selectable based on environment.  FIRST documented TS-Node
#      CLI library with renderer abstraction.
#
#   4. CONTEXT-PASSING — Every other documented TS-Node CLI
#      library has no inter-task context.  listr2 shares a `ctx`
#      object between tasks (TypeScript-typed via generics).
#      FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library with typed inter-task
#      context-passing.
#
#   5. ROLLBACK + RETRY — Every other documented TS-Node CLI
#      library has no retry or rollback semantics.  listr2 tasks
#      can specify `retry: N` for auto-retry and `rollback: fn`
#      for compensating undo on subsequent task failure.  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node CLI library with first-class retry +
#      rollback semantics.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/antiwork/shortest/blob/main/packages/shortest/
# src/cli/bin.ts + src/cli/commands/shortest.ts.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a commands=(
    'init:initialize shortest in current project'
    'github-code:run shortest against a GitHub repo'
    'cache:manage shortest test action cache'
    'detect-framework:detect web framework in current project'
    'analyze:analyze tests and generate insights'
    'plan:plan test execution without running'
    'generate:generate test specifications'
)

_arguments -s -C \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '--log-level=[set logging level]:level:(silly trace debug info warn error fatal silent)' \
    '--headless[run tests in headless browser mode]' \
    '--target=[set target URL for tests]:url:' \
    '--no-cache[disable test action caching]' \
    '1: :->cmd_or_pattern' \
    '*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    cmd_or_pattern)
        # First arg can be a subcommand or a test pattern (file or file:line)
        _alternative \
            "commands:shortest subcommand:(($commands))" \
            'patterns:test pattern (file or file\:line):_files -g "*.(test|spec).(ts|tsx|js|jsx)"' \
            && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case "${words[1]}" in
            cache)
                _arguments -s '1:subcommand:(clear)' && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
